<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1458,2025]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1566,1592]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[351,435,1566,1592]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Female</emphasis>
. Wing length 
<quantity box="[590,675,1566,1593]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
(2.4–2.8), width 
<quantity box="[866,951,1566,1593]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
(0.8–1.0). Flagellomeres 1–9 progressively slightly shorter, 10–12 progressively much shorter, first flagellomere 6x longer than wide [
<figureCitation box="[1178,1263,1602,1629]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,189,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 5a–g. Asphondylia ixora: a: gall on Ixora timorensis (Fig. 1016 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926); arrows indicate gall (ga) and normally developed ovary (ov); b-g, female: b, palpus; c, antenna; d, first tarsal segment; e, last tarsal segment of foreleg with claw and empodium; f, same of midleg; g, same of hindleg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406868/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5c</figureCitation>
]. Palpus 3-segmented, segments progressively longer [
<figureCitation box="[607,694,1638,1665]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,189,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 5a–g. Asphondylia ixora: a: gall on Ixora timorensis (Fig. 1016 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926); arrows indicate gall (ga) and normally developed ovary (ov); b-g, female: b, palpus; c, antenna; d, first tarsal segment; e, last tarsal segment of foreleg with claw and empodium; f, same of midleg; g, same of hindleg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406868/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5b</figureCitation>
]. First tarsal segment with apicoventral spur slightly curved [
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,189,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 5a–g. Asphondylia ixora: a: gall on Ixora timorensis (Fig. 1016 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926); arrows indicate gall (ga) and normally developed ovary (ov); b-g, female: b, palpus; c, antenna; d, first tarsal segment; e, last tarsal segment of foreleg with claw and empodium; f, same of midleg; g, same of hindleg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406868/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5d</figureCitation>
]. Tarsal claws strongly curved, anisomorphic, thinnest on forelegs, stout and widened at midlength on mid and hindlegs, empodia about as long as claws [
<figureCitation box="[638,711,1710,1737]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,189,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 5a–g. Asphondylia ixora: a: gall on Ixora timorensis (Fig. 1016 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926); arrows indicate gall (ga) and normally developed ovary (ov); b-g, female: b, palpus; c, antenna; d, first tarsal segment; e, last tarsal segment of foreleg with claw and empodium; f, same of midleg; g, same of hindleg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406868/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs 5</figureCitation>
e–g]. Needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor 2.0x longer than seventh sternite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1458,2025]" box="[199,519,1782,1808]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis box="[199,400,1782,1808]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Male, pupa, larva</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1238,1818,1845]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1458,2025]" box="[199,1238,1818,1845]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1818,1844]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Remarks</emphasis>
. The anisomorphic tarsal claws are unique among known Indonesian 
<taxonomicName box="[1091,1231,1818,1844]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1091,1231,1818,1844]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Asphondylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1458,2025]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1854,1880]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Biology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[305,513,1854,1880]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ixora">
<emphasis box="[305,513,1854,1880]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Asphondylia ixora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
causes the flower gall on 
<emphasis box="[818,1003,1855,1880]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ixora timorensis</emphasis>
described and illustrated by DvLR &amp; DvL (1926, gall No. 1433 Fig. 1016 [
<figureCitation box="[566,650,1890,1917]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,189,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 5a–g. Asphondylia ixora: a: gall on Ixora timorensis (Fig. 1016 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926); arrows indicate gall (ga) and normally developed ovary (ov); b-g, female: b, palpus; c, antenna; d, first tarsal segment; e, last tarsal segment of foreleg with claw and empodium; f, same of midleg; g, same of hindleg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406868/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5a</figureCitation>
]). The ovary is swollen into a sphere about 
<quantity box="[1135,1199,1890,1917]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
across, the surface is green and glossy, and inside is a spacious larval chamber surrounded by a succulent wall.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1458,2025]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,512,1962,1988]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Geographical distribution</emphasis>
